tags: I was almost in tears with happiness
title: Good Omens
body:
Spoilers below the cut

I. Loved. It. I’m going to say that first, because I need to say it. I was so excited and then I was smiling while I watched it and I loved it. It was so well done and just… great. A great adaptation.

I just binged 6 hours of TV and it’s waaay past my bed time, so I’m not going to get deeper into how much I loved it and all the things right now.

This is mostly because I need to get one thing out that I am slightly upset about, but I understand, because it probably wouldn’t have worked with the focus they took… and I get that not everyone’s favourite parts could make it. And I loved literally everything else. I have not been that happy about something I have watched in years. But I need to say this so I can get it out of the way and just love it. And because it is half past midnight and I need to sleep and I’m not going to be able to sleep until I’ve said this to someone, so I might as well scream it into the void, y’know?

I just… really wanted them to keep the ending. I may have mentioned it (once, twice, a million times), but it is literally my favourite ending of anything ever. The ending of Good Omens hits something on a deep level inside me. It resonates in this weird bittersweet way. And they had a narrator and I was waiting for the words, and they didn’t come.

And, looking at it, I get that the book ending wouldn’t have worked. I get that. But I need a moment to be sad about this, so I’m going to take this moment, and I’m going to be sad that they missed out the one thing that was the one thing I repeatedly said was all I wanted from this adaptation. But I refuse to let that diminish from the rest of it. Because it was glorious and beautiful and ineffable (and gayer than a tree full of monkeys on nitrous oxide). But I need my moment.

To imagine a summer that never ends. And a boy and a dog and his friends. And a sneaker, laces trailing. And a stick to poke at interesting things. And a whistle pounding some unsuspecting pop song into insensibility. I need a moment to imagine a boy, half demon, half angel, all human. Slouching towards Tadfield, forever.
